04551nam a22006975i 9780801463075DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014630757 a10.7591/97808014630752doi  a(DE-B1597)527325  a(OCoLC)956658953  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.868/72830732231 aReichman, Daniel R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Broken Village :bCoffee, Migration, and Globalization in Honduras /cDaniel R. Reichman. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b9 halftones, 2 charts/graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Integration and Disintegration -- t1. American Dream, American Work: Fantasies and Realities of Honduran Migrants -- t2. The Needy, the Greedy, and the Lazy: The Moral Universe of Migration -- t3. The Ashes of Progress: A Biography after Modernization -- t4. The Devil Has Been Destroyed: Mediation and Christian Citizenship -- t5. Justice at a Price: Risk and Regulation in the Global Coffee Market -- t6. Global Sociality, Postmodernity, and Neopopulism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Broken Village, Daniel R. Reichman tells the story of a remote village in Honduras that transformed almost overnight from a sleepy coffee-growing community to a hotbed of undocumented migration to and from the United States. The small village—called here by the pseudonym La Quebrada—was once home to a thriving coffee economy. Recently, it has become dependent on migrants working in distant places like Long Island and South Dakota, who live in ways that most Honduran townspeople struggle to comprehend or explain. Reichman explores how the new "migration economy" has upended cultural ideas of success and failure, family dynamics, and local politics.During his time in La Quebrada, Reichman focused on three different strategies for social reform—a fledgling coffee cooperative that sought to raise farmer incomes and establish principles of fairness and justice through consumer activism; religious campaigns for personal morality that were intended to counter the corrosive effects of migration; and local discourses about migrant "greed" that labeled migrants as the cause of social crisis, rather than its victims. All three phenomena had one common trait: They were settings in which people presented moral visions of social welfare in response to a perceived moment of crisis. The Broken Village integrates sacred and secular ideas of morality, legal and cultural notions of justice, to explore how different groups define social progress.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCoffee industryxSocial aspectszHonduras. 4aAnthropology. 4aLabor History. 4aLatin American & Caribbean Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146307540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801463075423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801463075.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK